Note: Asian Languages (Classifier-Based Systems)
Process called "determine_plural_category_asian" that takes count as Integer and language_code as String returns PluralCategory:
    Note: Handle Asian languages with classifier systems or no pluralization
    Match language_code:
    When "zh": Note: Chinese - no pluralization
            Return Other
    When "ja": Note: Japanese - no pluralization Return Other
    When "ko": Note: Korean - no pluralization
            Return Other
    When "th": Note: Thai - no pluralization
            Return Other
    When "vi": Note: Vietnamese - no pluralization
            Return Other
    Otherwise:
            Return determine_plural_category_generic with count as count

Note: Template Processing and Message Formatting
Process called "apply_pluralization_rules" that takes count as Integer and template as String and category as PluralCategory and rules as LanguageRules returns String:
    Note: Apply pluralization rules to message template
    Note: Parse template for plural forms - format: {count} {item|items}
            Let parts be parse_pluralization_template with template as template
            Let result be ""
    For each part in parts:
    If part.is_plural_placeholder:
            Let pluralized_part be select_plural_form with forms as part.plural_forms and category as category and count as count
            Set result to result pluralized_part
    Otherwise:
    Set result to result part.text Note: Replace count placeholder
            Set result to replace_count_placeholder with text as result and count as count Return result

Process called "select_plural_form" that takes forms as List[String] and category as PluralCategory and count as Integer returns String:
    Note: Select appropriate plural form based on category
    Match category:
    When Zero:
    If length of forms > 0:
            Return forms[0]
    Otherwise:
            Return Format.integer_to_string with value as count
    When One:
    If length of forms > 1:
            Return forms[1]
    Otherwise if length of forms > 0:
            Return forms[0]
    Otherwise:
            Return Format.integer_to_string with value as count
    When Two:
    If length of forms > 2:
            Return forms[2]
    Otherwise if length of forms > 1:
            Return forms[1]
    Otherwise:
            Return forms[0]
    When Few:
    If length of forms > 3:
            Return forms[3]
    Otherwise if length of forms > 1:
            Return forms[1]
    Otherwise:
            Return forms[0]
    When Many:
    If length of forms > 4:
            Return forms[4]
    Otherwise if length of forms > 1:
            Return forms[1]
    Otherwise:
            Return forms[0]
    When Other:
    If length of forms > 1:
    Return forms[1] Note: Use plural form
    Otherwise:
            Return forms[0]

Note: Ordinal Number Formatting
Process called "format_ordinal" that takes engine as PluralizationEngine and number as Integer and language_code as String returns String:
    Note: Format ordinal numbers with language-specific rules
    Let base_number be Format.integer_to_string with value as number If not engine.ordinal_rules contains key language_code:
            Return base_number get_default_ordinal_suffix with number as number Let ordinal_rules be engine.ordinal_rules[language_code]
            Let suffix be determine_ordinal_suffix with number as number and rules as ordinal_rules Return base_number suffix

Process called "determine_ordinal_suffix" that takes number as Integer and rules as OrdinalRules returns String:
    Note: Determine ordinal suffix based on language rules
            Let abs_number be absolute_value with value as number
            Let mod10 be abs_number mod 10
    Let mod100 be abs_number mod 100 Match rules.language_code:
    When "en": Note: English ordinals
    If mod100 > or equal to 11 and mod100 < or equal to 13:
            Return "th"
    Otherwise if mod10 = 1:
            Return "st"
    Otherwise if mod10 = 2:
            Return "nd"
    Otherwise if mod10 = 3:
            Return "rd"
    Otherwise:
            Return "th"
    When "fr": Note: French ordinals
    If abs_number = 1:
    Return "er" Note: premier
    Otherwise:
    Return "e" Note: deuxième, troisième, etc. When "de": Note: German ordinals
    Return "." Note: 1., 2., 3., etc. When "es": Note: Spanish ordinals
    If mod10 = 1 or mod10 = 3:
    Return "°" Note: 1°, 3°, etc.
    Otherwise:
    Return "°" Otherwise:
            Return ""

Note: Advanced Features and Utilities
Process called "create_supported_languages_list" returns List[String]:
    Note: Create list of all supported languages
    Return list containing:
            "en", "de", "fr", "es", "it", "pt", "nl", "sv", "da", "no",
            "pl", "ru", "cs", "sk", "hr", "sr", "bg", "sl", "mk", "uk",
            "ar", "he", "fa", "ur", "hi", "bn", "gu", "pa", "ta", "te",
            "fi", "et", "hu", "lv", "lt", "ro", "el", "tr", "id", "ms",
            "zh", "ja", "ko", "th", "vi", "tl", "sw", "am", "yo", "ig"

Process called "determine_plural_category" that takes count as Integer and rules as LanguageRules returns PluralCategory:
    Note: Main entry point for plural category determination
    Match rules.language_code:
    When "pl" or "ru" or "cs" or "hr" or "sk":
            Return determine_plural_category_slavic with count as count and language_code as rules.language_code
    When "ar":
            Return determine_plural_category_arabic with count as count
    When "fr" or "it" or "es" or "pt" or "ro":
            Return determine_plural_category_romance with count as count and language_code as rules.language_code
    When "en" or "de" or "nl" or "sv" or "da" or "no":
            Return determine_plural_category_germanic with count as count and language_code as rules.language_code
    When "fi" or "et" or "hu":
            Return determine_plural_category_finno_ugric with count as count and language_code as rules.language_code
    When "zh" or "ja" or "ko" or "th" or "vi":
            Return determine_plural_category_asian with count as count and language_code as rules.language_code
    Otherwise:
            Return determine_plural_category_generic with count as count

Process called "determine_plural_category_generic" that takes count as Integer returns PluralCategory:
    Note: Generic pluralization for languages with simple singular/plural distinction
            Let abs_count be absolute_value with value as count
    If abs_count = 1:
            Return One
    Otherwise:
            Return Other

Process called "absolute_value" that takes value as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Calculate absolute value of integer
    If value < 0:
            Return 0 - value
    Otherwise:
            Return value

Process called "parse_pluralization_template" that takes template as String returns List[TemplatePart]:
    Note: Parse template with plural forms - simplified implementation
    Let parts be list containing Note: For now, create a simple part representing the whole template
    Let part be TemplatePart with:
            text as template
            is_plural_placeholder as false
            plural_forms as list containing Add part to parts
            Return parts

Process called "replace_count_placeholder" that takes text as String and count as Integer returns String:
    Note: Replace {count} or {n} placeholders with actual count
            Let result be text
            Let count_str be Format.integer_to_string with value as count Set result to Format.replace_all with s as result and old as "{count}" and new as count_str
            Set result to Format.replace_all with s as result and old as "{n}" and new as count_str Return result

Process called "get_current_timestamp" returns Float:
    Note: Get current timestamp - would delegate to system in production
            Return 0.0

Process called "create_fallback_pluralization" that takes count as Integer and template as String returns PluralizationResult:
    Note: Create fallback pluralization for unsupported languages
    Return PluralizationResult with:
            pluralized_text as template
            applied_rule as "fallback"
            number_category as Other
            language_code as "unknown"
            confidence as 0.5
            alternative_forms as list containing
            grammatical_info as create_empty_grammatical_info
            metadata as dictionary containing "fallback" as true